    <stitle>CAB: 2000, 4000, AND 8000 - REMOVE AND INSTALL - CAB</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="4">
        <title>CAB</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Remove</title>
            <para>The removal of the cab from chassis can be performed providing an overhead crane and cab lifting
                fixture are available. Removal procedures may vary for various models depending on type of equipment and
                accessories.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Refer to the correct sections in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual for the component being
                        removed and replaced.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The following steps may be used as a guide.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block wheels of truck and engage parking brake.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tilt or remove hood.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect battery ground cable.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drain cooling system and disconnect heater hose.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect steering shaft at gear.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect accelerator linkage.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect electrical connections and ground wire.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect clutch linkage.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect brake system (air or hydraulic).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect air conditioning lines (if so equipped). Refer to GROUP 16 - CAB in the
                    CTS-5000 Master Service Manual for the proper procedure.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Do not vent refrigerant into the atmosphere. The use of R-12 is a worldwide environmental
                        concern. Because of the absence of chlorine in the molecular structure of R-134a, the use of
                        R-134a refrigerant will not have any harmful effects on the ozone layer of the atmosphere.
                        Because there is not enough evidence to determine the " greenhouse " effect of R-134a, recycling
                        of R-134a is recommended. Effective November 1995, recovery and recycling of R-134a will be
                        required by law.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove shift lever from transmission.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Detach exhaust system from cab if system is vertical type.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Detach any other connections between the cab and frame, if required.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install cab lifting fixture. Make sure fixture is padded to prevent damage to cab.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove cab to frame stay rods (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600744">Figure 44</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600744" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600744" filename="../figg16/G1600744.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 44. Cab to Frame Stay Rods</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. STAY ROD LOWER BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. STAY ROD</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. BOLT (3/8-16 UNC X 1-1/4)</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. STAY ROD UPPER BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. BOLT (1/2-20 UNF X 1-1/2; 1-3/4 W/REINFORCEMENT)</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. LOCKWASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. FLAT WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. STAY ROD INSULATOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. STABILIZER SPACER</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use an overhead crane and cab lifting fixture when removing the cab from the chassis. Pad the
                        lifting fixture to prevent damage to the cab assembly.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Partially lift cab so cab weight will be supported on lifting fixture.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove cab to frame mounting bolts and nuts at front and rear mounting locations (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600745">Figure 45</hotlnk>,
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600746">Figure 46</hotlnk>, and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600747">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600745" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600745" filename="../figg16/G1600745.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 45. Cab Front Mounting</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BOLT (1/2-13 X 3-1/4)</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. CAB REINFORCEMENT BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. DRAIN HOLE</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. SILL UNDERBODY ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. BRACKET ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. BOLT (1/2-13 UNC X 1-1/2)</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. BOLT (1/2-13 UNC X 1-1/2)</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. FLAT WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. INSULATOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>11. BOLT (1/2-13 UNC X 1-1/2)</callout1>
                        <callout1>12. CAB SAFETY STOP</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f1600746" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600746" filename="../figg16/G1600746.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 46. Cab Front Mounting</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. HEAT SHIELD</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BUTTON PLUG, B-CAB ONLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. CAB REINFORCEMENT MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. BOLT/WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. BOLT/WASHER/NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. CAB SAFETY STOP</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. CAB MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. BOLT/WASHER/NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. CAB MOUNTING INSULATOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. CAB MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f1600747" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600747" filename="../figg16/G1600747.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 47. Cab Rear Mounting</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BUTTON PLUG</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. CAB MOUNTING BOLT</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. CAB UNDERBODY SILL</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. TRANSMISSION MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. CAB REAR MOUNTING CROSSMEMBER</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. FLANGE TYPE NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. LOWER INSULATOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. CAB REAR MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. FLANGE HEAD BOLT</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. UPPER INSULATOR FRONT</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Inspect all cab to frame attaching points to be sure they are disconnected or damage can
                        result.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Carefully lift cab from chassis.</para>
            </step1>
            <para></para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Front Mounting</emph>
            </para>
            <para>80 inch (200 cm) wide cabs use a cab front mounting similar to those shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600745">Figure 45</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600746">Figure 46</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Rear Mounting</emph>
            </para>
            <para>The cab rear mounting is shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600747">Figure 47</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Install</title>
            <para>The installation of the cab onto the chassis can be performed providing an overhead crane and cab
                lifting fixture are available. Installation procedures may vary for various models depending on type of
                equipment and accessories.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lift cab with a suitable hoist. Position the cab over the chassis.</para>
            </step1>
            <para>Lower cab onto chassis and position over front and rear mounting locations (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600745">Figure 45</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600746">Figure 46</hotlnk>, and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600747">Figure 47</hotlnk>). Fasten with bolts and nuts and tighten to specifications
                in the
                <hotlnk document="s16007s_49.xml" xrefid="t1600703">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not put all cab weight on chassis until all mounting bolts are tightened.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position cab to frame stay rods and attach with washers, insulators, spacers, bolts and
                    nuts (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600744">Figure 44</hotlnk>). Tighten to specifications in the
                    <hotlnk document="s16007s_49.xml" xrefid="t1600703">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove cab lifting fixture.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The remaining steps can be performed with the aid of the appropriate service sections. Refer
                        to the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Attach exhaust system if it is the vertical type.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Attach shift lever to transmission.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect the following items:</para>
                <randlist type="dash">
                    <item>
                        <para>air conditioning lines (if so equipped). Refer to GROUP 16 - AIR CONDITIONING BASIC
                            THEORY, DIAGNOSIS AND SERVICE in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual for the proper
                            procedures to charge air conditioning system.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>brake system (air or hydraulic). Refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master Service
                            Manual for bleeding instructions.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>clutch linkage.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>electric connections and ground wire.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>accelerator linkage.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>steering shaft at gear.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>heater hose.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>adjust cab stay rods. Refer to
                            <hotlnk document="s16007s_X1600710.xml" xrefid="x1600710">STAY RODS.</hotlnk>.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fill cooling system. Refer to GROUP 12- COOLING in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual
                    for the proper coolant requirements and procedures.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect battery ground cable.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Replace or lower hood, unblock wheels, and release parking brake.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Road test vehicle. Be sure all vehicle components are operating properly before putting
                    vehicle back into service.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
